{{Orphan|date=May 2016}}

In algebra, a '''hypoalgebra''' is a generalization of a [[subalgebra]] of a [[Lie algebra]] introduced by {{harvtxt|Patera|Sharp|Slansky|1980}}. The relation between an algebra and a hypoalgebra is called a '''subjoining''' {{harv|Patera|Sharp|1980}}, which  generalizes the notion of an inclusion of subalgebras. There is also a notion of restriction of a representation of a Lie algebra to a subjoined hypoalgebra, with [[branching rule]]s similar to those for restriction to subalgebras except that some of the [[multiplicities]] in the branching rule may be negative. {{harvs|txt| last1=McKay | first1=W. G. | last3=Rand | first3=D. W. | last2=Patera | first2=J. |  year=1990}} calculated many of these branching rules for hypoalgebras.

