In [[mathematics]], the '''Macdonald identities''' are some infinite product identities associated to [[affine root system]]s, introduced by {{harvs|txt|authorlink=Ian G. Macdonald|first=Ian|last=Macdonald|year=1972}}. They include as special cases the [[Jacobi triple product identity]],  Watson's [[quintuple product identity]], several identities found by {{harvtxt|Dyson|1972}}, and a 10-fold product identity found by {{harvtxt|Winquist|1969}}.

{{harvtxt|Kac|1974}} and {{harvtxt|Moody|1975}} pointed out that the Macdonald identities are the analogs of the [[Weyl denominator formula]] for [[affine Kac–Moody algebra]]s and superalgebras.

